\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contrary to the commonly-used speckle tracking method, our approach employs
 several principal differences.
 We are using optical flow estimation for tracking the points of interest
 instead of correlation.
 However, the estimation of speckle movement is local only.
 The usage of generative probability shape model is used in order to preserve
 valid shape estimation of tracked LV.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Optical flow estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our experiments shown that the Pyramid Lucas-Kanade (PyrLK) method is a
 good choice for speckle motion estimation.
 It assumes that the difference in searching window between two consecutive
 frames is small.
 The general optical flow equation for the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{x}V_{x}+I_{y}V_{y}=-I_{t}\label{eq:OpticalFlow}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{t}$
\end_inset

 are the partial derives of image intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $I(x,y,t)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

 are desired components of flow velocity.
 The assumption of PyrLK method is that the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:OpticalFlow"

\end_inset

 holds for all points within specific window 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=q_{1},q_{2},\dots,q_{n}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
I_{x}(q_{1})V_{x}+I_{y}(q_{1})V_{y}=-I_{t}(q_{1})\\
I_{x}(q_{2})V_{x}+I_{y}(q_{2})V_{y}=-I_{t}(q_{2})\\
\vdots\\
I_{x}(q_{n})V_{x}+I_{y}(q_{n})V_{y}=-I_{t}(q_{n})
\end{array}\label{eq:LKOpticalFlow}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we substitute
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=\begin{bmatrix}I_{x}(q_{1}) & I_{y}(q_{1})\\
I_{x}(q_{2}) & I_{y}(q_{2})\\
\vdots & \vdots\\
I_{x}(q_{n}) & I_{y}(q_{n})
\end{bmatrix}\mbox{, }v=\begin{bmatrix}V_{x}\\
V_{y}
\end{bmatrix}\mbox{, and }b=\begin{bmatrix}-I_{t}(q_{1})\\
-I_{t}(q_{1})\\
\vdots\\
I_{t}(q_{n})
\end{bmatrix}\label{eq:LKSolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we obtain a matrix form of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LKOpticalFlow"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Av=b\label{eq:LKOpticalFlowMatrixForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The least-square solution of the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LKOpticalFlowMatrixForm"

\end_inset

 is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v=(A^{T}A)^{-1}A^{T}b
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
TODO: PyrLK
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Statistical shape model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The PyrLK point tracker provides robust technique for following and individual
 points of interest.
 However, it is important to maintain a specific shape of the LV during
 cardiac cycle.
 We are using a statistical shape model that has been previously described
 in TODO:ref Cootes.
 The main idea of statistical shape models is employment of probability
 density model.
 Some arbitrary shape 
\begin_inset Formula $s=((x_{1},y_{1}),(x_{2},y_{2}),\dots,(x_{n},y_{n}))$
\end_inset

 can be unambiguously represented as a column vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}=[x_{1},y_{1},x_{2},y_{2},\dots,x_{n},y_{n}]^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 Modeling of the shape variation is accomplished using Principal Component
 Analysis (PCA).
 In order to do that, calculations in the following steps are executed:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Mean vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\bar{s}}$
\end_inset

 of all shapes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{\bar{s}}=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}\mathbf{s}_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Covariance matrix 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{S}=\frac{1}{N-1}\sum_{i=1}^{N}(\mathbf{s}_{i}-\mathbf{\bar{s}})(\mathbf{s}_{i}-\mathbf{\bar{s}})^{T}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute the eigenvectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\phi}_{1},\dots,\boldsymbol{\phi}_{m}$
\end_inset

 and corresponding eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\lambda}_{1},\dots,\boldsymbol{\lambda}_{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Create projection matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Phi}=(\boldsymbol{\phi}_{1}|\boldsymbol{\phi}_{2}|\dots|\boldsymbol{\phi}_{t})$
\end_inset

 that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 largest eigenvalues from previous step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, every shape 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 can be represented in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-dimensional PCA space:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{b}=\boldsymbol{\Phi}^{T}(\mathbf{s}-\mathbf{\bar{s}})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our LV shape model consist of 93 points that were manually annotated from
 4 LV cycles from 2 subjects.
 In each frame, the human operator annotated points on the mid-myocardium.
 The computer inserted spline between points and 31 new equally-distanced
 points were interpolated.
 Each point was triplicated, such that the 93 inner points outlined inner
 myocardium and outer 93 points outlined outer myocardium.
 Since we are interested in contraction of individual parts of the myocardium,
 the spacing variations between points were added to the base set of shapes.
\end_layout

