\begin_layout Subsection
Algorithm description
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our tracking algorithm consists of individua function blocks where each
 block deals with a specific task and can be easily replaced with another
 block that solves the same problem, e.g., the image processing block can
 be be empty or consists of several consecutive image filters.
 See Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Algorithm-pipeline"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig/pipeline.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Algorithm pipeline
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Algorithm-pipeline"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The image transformation block transforms the input image from the input
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mbox{-}y$
\end_inset

 coordinate system to the angle-distance (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\mbox{-}d$
\end_inset

) coordinate system.
 The center of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\mbox{-}d$
\end_inset

 coordinate system is placed to the center of the circular sector that contains
 image data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig/coords.png
	width 8cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Image transformation from 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mbox{-}y$
\end_inset

 coordinate system to the angle-distance (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\mbox{-}d$
\end_inset

) coordinate system
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The image processing block involves the application of image filters to
 the transformed frame.
 We have tested contrast enhancement, histogram equalization, edge detection,
 sharpening, and noise reduction in our experiments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The point tracking block has three inputs - the previous frame, the annotated
 points within the previous frame, and the next frame, where the point tracking
 algorithm should find the desired points.
 The next frame is also processed with image transformation and filters.
 Additionaly to the PyrLK point tracker, we have implemented speckle tracking
 based on the minimizing the Euclidean distance, correlation metric, or
 sum of absolute differences between the neighbour of tracked point in previous
 frame and potential position of the point in the next frame (see Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Point-tracking"

\end_inset

).
 Let the pixel intensity neighbourhood of the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

.
 The shift of the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 between the previous and the next frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\triangle x=\arg\min_{i\in I}\left\Vert \mathbb{\mathbf{x}}-\mathbf{x}_{i}\right\Vert 
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the pixel intensity neighbourhood of the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the next frame.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig/point-tracking.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

